            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> am I correct in thinking that flask is in development mode both when running on the builtin server with debug=False and when running on (say) uwsgi with debug=True?\r\n\r\nI would avoid using \"development mode\" in reference to a Flask application altogether. For consistency, I think the mode should always be called \"debug mode\". I think calling the opposite of debug mode \"production mode\" is also a bit misleading, since this is a mode that you can certainly run on the Flask development server, which is not meant to be used in production.\r\n\r\nSo regarding your question @dradetsky, in my opinion there is just \"debug mode\", and it can be on or off, regardless of the server being the builtin one or uwsgi, gunicorn, etc.\r\n\r\nThere are a couple more references to \"production mode\" and 'development mode\" in the docs besides the one you found that I think would also benefit if they are rephrased in terms of debug mode."
